1
00:01:07,745 --> 00:01:09,107
When shall I pick you up, sir?

2
00:01:11,384 --> 00:01:13,062
Give me time for a couple of cocktails.

3
00:01:13,449 --> 00:01:14,693
Half an hour.
- Yes, sir.

4
00:01:14,938 --> 00:01:17,999
Mrs Farnsworth asked me to remind you
of your dinner engagement tonight.

5
00:01:18,437 --> 00:01:20,737
A half-hour will just give me
time to change and make it.

6
00:01:21,344 --> 00:01:22,159
By the way.

7
00:01:22,508 --> 00:01:24,638
Did Mrs Farnsworth mention
with whom we dine?

8
00:01:24,964 --> 00:01:26,744
With the Lindens, sir.
- Oh.

9
00:01:27,105 --> 00:01:27,990
The Lindens.

10
00:01:29,398 --> 00:01:31,406
You'd better make it an hour, Williams.

11
00:01:31,822 --> 00:01:34,645
I find I'll need more
cocktails than I thought.

12
00:01:47,487 --> 00:01:50,461
I beg your pardon .. but
aren't you Joyce Heath?

13
00:01:51,977 --> 00:01:53,372
No.
- But I ..

14
00:01:53,863 --> 00:01:55,024
You've made a mistake.

15
00:01:57,513 --> 00:02:00,076
Perhaps I have .. pardon me.

16
00:02:10,926 --> 00:02:11,855
Gentlemen.

17
00:02:12,192 --> 00:02:14,517
How are you, Mr Farnsworth?
- Evening, Roger.

18
00:02:15,521 --> 00:02:18,907
Anthony, a Sidecar with just a
splash more brandy than necessary.

19
00:02:19,640 --> 00:02:22,690
I suppose you know what brandy
does to your liver, Roger.

20
00:02:22,957 --> 00:02:25,348
Yes. That's why I stopped
port and turned to brandy.

21
00:02:25,561 --> 00:02:28,044
Your liver is far less
conspicuous than your nose.

22
00:02:29,441 --> 00:02:31,715
Do you chaps remember
an actress Joyce Heath?

23
00:02:32,253 --> 00:02:35,216
I'll never forget her
as Camille .. Sappho.

24
00:02:35,585 --> 00:02:37,678
I saw her only once,
but I'll never forget her.

25
00:02:38,339 --> 00:02:40,872
What a vitally tempestuous
creature she was.

26
00:02:41,431 --> 00:02:44,795
It's amazing how a powerful personality
can project itself over the footlights.

27
00:02:45,625 --> 00:02:47,411
That night I was in
the rear of the theater.

28
00:02:47,614 --> 00:02:49,724
Yet couldn't have been closer
if I held her in my arms.

29
00:02:49,927 --> 00:02:51,705
Not closer perhaps,
but more interesting.

30
00:02:52,043 --> 00:02:54,418
Quiet .. let the gentleman confess.

31
00:02:54,703 --> 00:02:55,965
Joyce Heath never knew it.

32
00:02:56,199 --> 00:02:59,442
But she prompted me to make a decision
that remade the course of my whole life.

33
00:03:00,987 --> 00:03:04,385
The career my family planned for
me in Wall Street I discarded.

34
00:03:04,936 --> 00:03:06,711
I suddenly got the urge to create.

35
00:03:07,430 --> 00:03:10,216
I gave up writing as I couldn't write,
and music because I couldn't play.

36
00:03:10,419 --> 00:03:11,498
But I could draw.

37
00:03:12,266 --> 00:03:14,007
Three years in Paris taught me ..

38
00:03:14,830 --> 00:03:16,606
Not defeat .. but compromise.

39
00:03:17,438 --> 00:03:19,821
I still had enough of the
urge left to try architecture.

40
00:03:20,429 --> 00:03:23,032
I saw her tonight, just as I came in.

41
00:03:23,442 --> 00:03:24,888
Dowdy, down and out.

42
00:03:25,297 --> 00:03:27,043
And ashamed of being Joyce Heath.

43
00:03:27,621 --> 00:03:28,791
She was tops.

44
00:03:30,207 --> 00:03:32,438
What's the matter, Mr Hanley?
Isn't the Highball right?

45
00:03:32,719 --> 00:03:35,432
Oh .. the Highball. Yes, perfect.

46
00:03:35,851 --> 00:03:36,580
Why?

47
00:03:37,044 --> 00:03:39,262
You looked as if something
tasted or smelt bad.

48
00:03:39,994 --> 00:03:42,797
I would rather you wouldn't mention
that. I was reading my own column.

49
00:03:43,405 --> 00:03:45,101
Ted.
- Yeah?

50
00:03:45,769 --> 00:03:47,149
We want to ask you something.

51
00:03:47,937 --> 00:03:49,473
Yes, it's a toupee.

52
00:03:51,608 --> 00:03:54,256
What about Joyce Heath? She was a star.

53
00:03:55,184 --> 00:03:57,686
She was too brilliant.
Too startling for a star.

54
00:03:58,196 --> 00:03:59,255
She was a comet.

55
00:03:59,592 --> 00:04:02,002
Which appeared suddenly.
Fell spectacularly.

56
00:04:02,339 --> 00:04:03,666
And disappeared completely.

57
00:04:04,099 --> 00:04:06,883
That, gentlemen, is a metaphor.
One of the great actresses.

58
00:04:07,161 --> 00:04:08,119
And Joyce Heath.

59
00:04:08,322 --> 00:04:10,963
That's why I can't read his column.
He writes that way too.

60
00:04:11,906 --> 00:04:13,438
Yes, but what happened to her, Ted?

61
00:04:13,641 --> 00:04:16,959
Fantastic as it may sound .. a jinx.
One she put on other people.

62
00:04:17,167 --> 00:04:18,175
A jinx?

63
00:04:18,554 --> 00:04:21,530
It started when her leading man
was killed on an opening night.

64
00:04:22,295 --> 00:04:27,107
From then on .. everyone associated with
her was haunted by failures, divorces ..

65
00:04:27,544 --> 00:04:28,732
Suicides and scandals.

66
00:04:28,960 --> 00:04:31,658
That's right. She practically
lived on the front page.

67
00:04:32,366 --> 00:04:34,311
At first, she laughed
at the superstition.

68
00:04:34,670 --> 00:04:35,771
Then she believed it.

69
00:04:36,466 --> 00:04:39,274
Last time I saw her, she was
on a cheap Vaudeville tour.

70
00:04:39,773 --> 00:04:42,685
Then she vanished.
Like the magician's lady.

71
00:04:44,431 --> 00:04:46,169
Sounds almost unbelievable, doesn't it.

72
00:04:47,763 --> 00:04:48,780
But it happened.

73
00:04:52,002 --> 00:04:55,306
I have to break into a trot if I want
to change and pick up Gail in time.

74
00:04:55,683 --> 00:04:57,398
We have a dinner date.
- The Lindens?

75
00:04:57,849 --> 00:04:58,790
The Lindens.

76
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:02,200
I think they get most of their guests
from the tomb of Ramses The Second.

77
00:05:02,720 --> 00:05:05,042
There's quite a few valuable
civil war relics among them too.

78
00:05:05,696 --> 00:05:06,796
Goodnight.
- Night.

79
00:05:07,129 --> 00:05:08,002
A clever boy.

80
00:05:08,205 --> 00:05:09,934
One of the best architects
in the country.

81
00:05:10,137 --> 00:05:13,641
With his reputation and Gail Armitage
connections he'll come out alright.

82
00:05:14,163 --> 00:05:15,772
By the way, when will they be married?

83
00:05:15,975 --> 00:05:18,199
It hasn't been arranged yet.
- How do you know?

84
00:05:19,005 --> 00:05:20,601
Mrs Farnsworth hasn't heard.

85
00:05:21,599 --> 00:05:23,111
Maybe they're keeping it a secret?

86
00:05:23,314 --> 00:05:25,317
What, from my wife? Impossible.

87
00:05:36,876 --> 00:05:38,428
Good evening, Cato.
- Good evening.

88
00:05:40,004 --> 00:05:43,813
I'm late, Cato. You'd better draw me a
bath, lay out my dinner jacket and ..

89
00:05:44,133 --> 00:05:45,439
Never mind the bath.

90
00:05:45,768 --> 00:05:49,157
Did you ever try putting celluloid fish
in the tub to entice him into it, Cato?

91
00:05:49,574 --> 00:05:51,138
Gail, what are you doing here?

92
00:05:51,349 --> 00:05:54,424
I finished early, so I came over to save
you the bother of driving out to get me.

93
00:05:54,711 --> 00:05:55,739
Good for you.

94
00:05:57,367 --> 00:05:59,355
Cato .. stew up a cocktail.

95
00:06:00,022 --> 00:06:01,549
I don't want a cocktail, thank you.

96
00:06:02,170 --> 00:06:04,741
Some hors d'oeuvres, Cato.
- They always spoil my dinner.

97
00:06:05,887 --> 00:06:08,930
Cato, you fix the young lady a ham
sandwich whether she wants it or not.

98
00:06:14,328 --> 00:06:16,287
Gail, what do you think?
- That I love you.

99
00:06:16,694 --> 00:06:18,310
I'm pretty fond of myself this evening.

100
00:06:18,586 --> 00:06:20,388
The bank is going to
make the building loan.

101
00:06:20,673 --> 00:06:23,215
Don, how marvelous.
- Miraculous is the word.

102
00:06:23,418 --> 00:06:25,483
All I have to do is put a
hundred thousand in escrow.

103
00:06:26,046 --> 00:06:27,773
But they could let you
have the land now.

104
00:06:27,976 --> 00:06:30,353
Don't worry about the petty cash.
It will come out alright.

105
00:06:30,694 --> 00:06:33,927
Think of really starting on the estates,
after dreaming about them for years.

106
00:06:34,130 --> 00:06:35,850
I know exactly how
they're going to look.

107
00:06:36,090 --> 00:06:39,064
Unless I fall down, they'll be the most
beautiful estates in the whole country.

108
00:06:40,070 --> 00:06:41,246
And I can't fall down.

109
00:06:41,509 --> 00:06:43,762
I've worked too hard,
I've waited too long to flop.

110
00:06:44,363 --> 00:06:46,893
It seems as though it's all really
going to come through, doesn't it.

111
00:06:47,809 --> 00:06:49,425
I guess we have everything, young lady.

112
00:06:49,841 --> 00:06:51,305
And best of all, we have us.

113
00:06:51,936 --> 00:06:53,148
Ham sandwich, please?

114
00:06:57,050 --> 00:06:59,221
No mustard.
- No mustard?

115
00:06:59,564 --> 00:07:01,944
No mustard.
- Cato, go look for some mustard.

116
00:07:02,260 --> 00:07:05,590
If you find it and bring it here, you'll
go out of here looking like a hot-dog.

117
00:07:09,368 --> 00:07:10,877
Happy?
- Ecstatically.

118
00:07:11,260 --> 00:07:11,909
Why?

119
00:07:12,229 --> 00:07:15,361
Because dear, I have a very good sense.

120
00:07:16,419 --> 00:07:17,786
You ineffable cad, you.

121
00:07:18,139 --> 00:07:19,911
You adorable darling, you.

122
00:07:22,606 --> 00:07:24,878
Darling, hurry. Get dressed or
we'll be late for the Lindens.

123
00:07:25,081 --> 00:07:27,740
Can't we get out of it somehow?
- No, we cannot.

124
00:07:28,025 --> 00:07:30,515
You'll meet a lot of people there
who can afford to buy your houses.

125
00:07:30,728 --> 00:07:33,657
People who go to the Lindens don't
need houses, they need tombs.

126
00:07:44,309 --> 00:07:45,443
[ Meow ]

127
00:07:47,433 --> 00:07:48,899
Woof, woof.
- Meow.

128
00:07:54,661 --> 00:07:56,518
Gail and I couldn't stand it any longer.

129
00:07:56,747 --> 00:08:00,774
Being the extra man at a Linden party
is like being a spare corpse at a wake.

130
00:08:01,396 --> 00:08:03,211
I could kiss you for
getting us out of there.

131
00:08:03,414 --> 00:08:06,003
I could too, if you didn't look so much
like a horse that threw me once.

132
00:08:06,846 --> 00:08:08,610
Be exact. There have been so many.

133
00:08:09,603 --> 00:08:11,075
Delightful women you take up with.

134
00:08:11,325 --> 00:08:12,283
Where to, shrew?

135
00:08:12,737 --> 00:08:13,647
What can I do?

136
00:08:13,850 --> 00:08:15,352
Steal watermelons?
- Get tattooed?

137
00:08:15,555 --> 00:08:17,288
Paint mustaches on a library lion.

138
00:08:17,520 --> 00:08:20,104
One of you are bound to say
something rude if this goes on.

139
00:08:20,652 --> 00:08:22,983
I'd like to go to shooting galleries
and Honkytonks and things.

140
00:08:23,281 --> 00:08:24,069
An idea.

141
00:08:24,971 --> 00:08:27,494
I'll send my driver home, and
we'll all go with you in your car.

142
00:08:27,816 --> 00:08:30,631
No you won't. I've a tough day tomorrow.
I want to get up early.

143
00:08:31,031 --> 00:08:34,835
I don't want to spend tonight escorting
you in, and carrying you out of a club.

144
00:08:35,094 --> 00:08:37,416
Say, listen. I've never been
carried to any place in my life.

145
00:08:38,195 --> 00:08:40,880
Thrown, yes .. but carried, never.
Well, whisk away and I'll follow.

146
00:09:06,213 --> 00:09:07,555
Come on. Let's not go home.

147
00:09:07,780 --> 00:09:09,975
Let's go in here and splash
about in some birds nest soup.

148
00:09:10,178 --> 00:09:12,451
How about a little high
class sharpshooting?

149
00:09:12,849 --> 00:09:15,002
A harbor for flotsam and jetsam.
A bit of O'Henry's.

150
00:09:15,306 --> 00:09:16,035
You win.

151
00:09:28,023 --> 00:09:29,300
A smart looking place.

152
00:09:29,713 --> 00:09:30,982
Whose idea was this?

153
00:09:32,349 --> 00:09:33,528
We can sit here.

154
00:09:34,222 --> 00:09:35,882
I guess we'd better stand at the bar.

155
00:09:36,805 --> 00:09:38,653
You'd better sit where
he tells you to, dear.

156
00:10:01,217 --> 00:10:03,997
Oh Don, this is such a depressing place.
- You don't want to stay?

157
00:10:04,298 --> 00:10:05,965
No, let's get out of here. Come on.

158
00:10:09,323 --> 00:10:10,399
Some other time.

159
00:10:17,160 --> 00:10:19,693
You can chalk one up against me.
I certainly can pick them.

160
00:10:20,811 --> 00:10:21,689
Now where?

161
00:10:23,342 --> 00:10:25,461
It's after 12 o'clock.
Don has to get to bed.

162
00:10:25,855 --> 00:10:27,597
He's been working like a Trojan lately.

163
00:10:28,355 --> 00:10:31,126
Why don't you go on with Teddy.
Let him take you home.

164
00:10:32,493 --> 00:10:34,676
It would save me an hour,
getting out and back.

165
00:10:35,003 --> 00:10:36,062
Do you mind, Teddy?

166
00:10:36,348 --> 00:10:39,486
No. Not if you don't talk about Don.
- Alright. Why don't you do it then?

167
00:10:39,862 --> 00:10:42,370
I think I will. I've got an early
meeting in the morning.

168
00:10:42,643 --> 00:10:43,873
I'll call you after that.

169
00:10:44,076 --> 00:10:45,390
Don't forget.
- No.

170
00:10:45,653 --> 00:10:48,442
Listen, you're coming out to the club to
see me play Polo next week aren't you?

171
00:10:48,826 --> 00:10:52,235
You mean to see the horseplay
until you get tired? I might.

172
00:10:52,941 --> 00:10:53,727
Goodnight.

173
00:10:54,383 --> 00:10:55,427
Goodnight, darling.

174
00:10:55,720 --> 00:10:57,242
Goodnight.
- Goodnight.

175
00:11:34,749 --> 00:11:36,116
Do you mind if I sit down?

176
00:11:37,408 --> 00:11:40,326
Not if you buy a drink.
- Two of whatever the lady is drinking.

177
00:11:40,667 --> 00:11:41,598
Straight gin.

178
00:11:47,320 --> 00:11:48,639
I've seen you before.

179
00:11:48,842 --> 00:11:50,877
Which doesn't make us old friends.

180
00:11:53,693 --> 00:11:55,150
Well you see, one time, I ..

181
00:11:55,383 --> 00:11:57,831
It really doesn't interest
me, if you don't mind.

182
00:12:02,336 --> 00:12:03,042
Thanks.

183
00:12:04,740 --> 00:12:05,555
Not at all.

184
00:12:08,983 --> 00:12:10,289
Rather ironical, isn't it?

185
00:12:12,400 --> 00:12:13,829
Are you going to drink that?

186
00:12:15,039 --> 00:12:16,298
Haven't you had enough?

187
00:12:18,861 --> 00:12:19,733
Quite enough.

188
00:12:27,759 --> 00:12:28,917
Goodnight, Joyce Heath.

189
00:12:33,068 --> 00:12:34,127
What did you say?

190
00:12:34,585 --> 00:12:35,831
Joyce Heath.

191
00:12:37,130 --> 00:12:37,881
I ..

192
00:12:39,639 --> 00:12:41,400
Joyce Heath, the actress.

193
00:12:41,734 --> 00:12:45,105
Sitting in a dive like this
swilling down cheap gin?

194
00:12:46,592 --> 00:12:48,057
You must be drunk too.

195
00:12:48,477 --> 00:12:51,109
No, there isn't much similarity
except in appearance.

196
00:12:52,228 --> 00:12:53,850
Lots of people look alike.

197
00:12:54,541 --> 00:12:56,079
Joyce Heath was full of life.

198
00:12:57,108 --> 00:12:59,744
I'll never forget the time I saw her.
She was playing Juliet.

199
00:13:01,456 --> 00:13:05,895
Do you remember the scene where you
were told you had to marry Count Paris?

200
00:13:06,421 --> 00:13:09,905
And you took the sleeping draught to
pretend death until Romeo's return?

201
00:13:11,347 --> 00:13:12,934
As your mother kissed you goodnight ..

202
00:13:13,165 --> 00:13:14,037
And left you.

203
00:13:15,088 --> 00:13:15,874
You began:

204
00:13:16,747 --> 00:13:17,573
'Farewell'.

205
00:13:18,760 --> 00:13:20,795
'God knows when we shall meet again'.

206
00:13:21,482 --> 00:13:22,683
Farewell.

207
00:13:23,997 --> 00:13:26,288
God knows when we shall meet again.

208
00:13:28,518 --> 00:13:31,785
A faint, cold fear thrills my veins.

209
00:13:33,564 --> 00:13:36,630
And almost freezes out the heat of life.

210
00:13:40,323 --> 00:13:42,388
I shall call them back to comfort me.

211
00:13:44,596 --> 00:13:45,478
Nurse.

212
00:13:47,415 --> 00:13:48,940
What should she do here?

213
00:13:50,611 --> 00:13:53,645
My needs must act my dismal scene alone.

214
00:13:56,369 --> 00:13:57,443
Come, vial.

215
00:13:59,909 --> 00:14:02,112
What if this mixture do not work?

216
00:14:03,762 --> 00:14:06,699
Shall I, by force, be
married to the Count?

217
00:14:08,388 --> 00:14:09,019
No.

218
00:14:11,190 --> 00:14:12,969
No .. this shall ..

219
00:14:14,561 --> 00:14:15,493
This shall ..

220
00:14:21,016 --> 00:14:21,887
Passed out?

221
00:14:22,213 --> 00:14:23,004
Seems so.

222
00:14:23,295 --> 00:14:24,403
I'll call the wagon.

223
00:14:24,606 --> 00:14:26,990
They'll throw her in the tank until
she comes to in the morning.

224
00:14:27,544 --> 00:14:28,257
Waiter.

225
00:14:30,414 --> 00:14:31,458
I'll take her home.

226
00:14:32,216 --> 00:14:35,368
Okay buddy. Pay me twenty cents
for them two drinks and she's yours.

227
00:14:40,632 --> 00:14:42,371
Keep the change, boss?
- Yes.

228
00:14:43,159 --> 00:14:43,802
Okay.

229
00:15:34,803 --> 00:15:35,974
[ Door knocks ]

230
00:15:38,182 --> 00:15:38,948
Yes?

231
00:15:46,967 --> 00:15:47,965
You look poorly.

232
00:15:49,632 --> 00:15:51,792
Then it won't surprise you to be
told that I <i>feel</i> poorly.

233
00:15:52,291 --> 00:15:52,877
No.

234
00:15:53,672 --> 00:15:56,243
Figuring the moist condition
you arrived in last night.

235
00:15:57,099 --> 00:16:00,299
And just where did I arrive? I'm not
asking you to betray a confidence.

236
00:16:01,372 --> 00:16:02,949
This is Mr Bellows' place.

237
00:16:03,362 --> 00:16:04,385
He's an architect.

238
00:16:04,999 --> 00:16:06,704
One of them fellows who draws pictures.

239
00:16:07,184 --> 00:16:07,970
Thank you.

240
00:16:08,784 --> 00:16:10,327
I suppose you are Mrs Bellows?

241
00:16:10,996 --> 00:16:12,526
Or are you just one of his sketches?

242
00:16:12,858 --> 00:16:13,501
Nope.

243
00:16:14,165 --> 00:16:17,063
I'm his housekeeper for when
he comes down here weekends.

244
00:16:18,235 --> 00:16:20,829
How cozy. And Mr Bellows, where is he?

245
00:16:21,160 --> 00:16:22,289
He's having breakfast.

246
00:16:22,909 --> 00:16:26,454
And if you want to see him, you better
look perky. He's got to get to town.

247
00:16:27,062 --> 00:16:29,250
I'm looking forward
to seeing Mr Bellows.

248
00:16:32,359 --> 00:16:33,756
Stop that.
- Leave me alone.

249
00:16:34,070 --> 00:16:36,412
I wasn't going to push you ..
- Do you mind leaving me alone?

250
00:16:36,754 --> 00:16:38,874
Nope .. in fact, I'd like it.

251
00:16:51,899 --> 00:16:52,927
Well, she's up.

252
00:16:54,481 --> 00:16:55,195
Oh.

253
00:16:55,540 --> 00:16:58,124
I bet the Mahoney boys are having
a parade for her this morning.

254
00:16:58,683 --> 00:17:00,231
There weren't no-one in her room.

255
00:17:01,146 --> 00:17:03,257
I don't know the Mahoney boys anyhow.

256
00:17:03,745 --> 00:17:05,322
You never heard of the Mahoney Boys?

257
00:17:05,638 --> 00:17:06,775
You're very fortunate.

258
00:17:07,373 --> 00:17:08,856
Tiny men with purple beards.

259
00:17:09,059 --> 00:17:11,750
That play tunes with nail-files
on your teeth with one hand ..

260
00:17:11,956 --> 00:17:14,199
And keep time with mallets
inside your head with the other.

261
00:17:14,597 --> 00:17:17,304
At the same time they run around your
stomach planting jumping beans.

262
00:17:18,141 --> 00:17:20,477
You wouldn't be pulling my
leg would you Mr Bellows?

263
00:17:21,078 --> 00:17:22,839
Please .. Mrs Williams.

264
00:17:41,004 --> 00:17:42,596
Feeling better?
- I'd like a drink.

265
00:17:44,076 --> 00:17:45,132
Before breakfast?

266
00:17:46,040 --> 00:17:47,195
Get me a drink.

267
00:17:59,469 --> 00:18:00,941
Why don't you lay off that stuff?

268
00:18:01,312 --> 00:18:02,946
Because I'd rather be drunk than sober.

269
00:18:03,149 --> 00:18:04,632
I gathered that last night.

270
00:18:05,451 --> 00:18:06,310
Last night?

271
00:18:07,225 --> 00:18:09,217
Oh, you must be quite
proud of your conquest.

272
00:18:09,735 --> 00:18:11,629
You're very wrong. You see, I ..

273
00:18:11,832 --> 00:18:13,820
Don't bother with alibis.
It really doesn't matter.

274
00:18:15,975 --> 00:18:17,425
You are a perfect alibi.

275
00:18:17,939 --> 00:18:19,701
Take a look at yourself.
Take a good look.

276
00:18:19,904 --> 00:18:21,203
Drunken. Ill-kept.

277
00:18:21,520 --> 00:18:23,671
The only feeling you can
arouse in a man is pity.

278
00:18:23,906 --> 00:18:24,571
Pity?

279
00:18:25,870 --> 00:18:28,406
Pity? You dare to feel sorry for me.

280
00:18:28,758 --> 00:18:31,258
You with your fat little
soul and your smug face.

281
00:18:31,612 --> 00:18:34,172
Picking your way so cautiously
through a pastel existence.

282
00:18:34,766 --> 00:18:37,050
Why, I've lived more in a day
than you'll ever dare live.

283
00:18:37,463 --> 00:18:38,496
Pity for me?

284
00:18:38,742 --> 00:18:41,504
That's very funny, when I've
never had any for men like you.

285
00:18:46,720 --> 00:18:48,907
You know, just now you are
as I imagined you would be.

286
00:18:49,961 --> 00:18:51,970
Playing a second act speech
in a third-act coat.

287
00:18:52,246 --> 00:18:54,732
When you boast to your friends
about seeing me here ..

288
00:18:55,837 --> 00:18:58,528
I shouldn't mention that
I've become a has-been.

289
00:18:59,412 --> 00:19:02,388
It would detract frightfully from
the glamour of your adventure.

290
00:19:02,956 --> 00:19:05,066
Look here, Miss Heath.
The reason I brought you here ..

291
00:19:05,269 --> 00:19:07,134
I know. Because you were sorry for me.

292
00:19:07,666 --> 00:19:08,881
You've already said that.

293
00:19:09,210 --> 00:19:09,796
No.

294
00:19:10,479 --> 00:19:13,790
Because I was grateful to you for
something very important in my life.

295
00:19:15,146 --> 00:19:17,008
I suppose you always loved the theater.

296
00:19:17,735 --> 00:19:18,864
It was more than that.

297
00:19:20,241 --> 00:19:23,126
The beauty and fineness of one of your
performances moved me so strongly ..

298
00:19:23,329 --> 00:19:25,347
That the whole pattern
of my life was altered.

299
00:19:26,125 --> 00:19:27,886
I've had plenty to be grateful for.

300
00:19:28,452 --> 00:19:30,544
But first of all I owe you
my deepest gratitude.

301
00:19:31,808 --> 00:19:32,565
Well?

302
00:19:35,273 --> 00:19:37,683
Then I'm humiliated to the
point where I must thank you.

303
00:19:48,107 --> 00:19:50,333
Breakfast .. breakfast ..

304
00:19:51,074 --> 00:19:51,884
Oh.

305
00:19:53,184 --> 00:19:54,657
Smoking before breakfast.

306
00:19:55,557 --> 00:19:57,045
You'll spoil your appetite.

307
00:19:57,496 --> 00:19:59,071
Being here already has.

308
00:20:13,082 --> 00:20:14,539
Restful here, isn't it.

309
00:20:15,460 --> 00:20:17,528
The whole countryside
seems to have found peace.

310
00:20:18,540 --> 00:20:20,908
A person could find peace too.
- No.

311
00:20:22,350 --> 00:20:25,623
You only find that in yourself and
when you do you may as well be dead.

312
00:20:26,030 --> 00:20:26,961
Dead?

313
00:20:28,158 --> 00:20:29,953
'Rest In Peace' is for tombstones.

314
00:20:30,788 --> 00:20:32,094
And for the living?

315
00:20:33,039 --> 00:20:34,934
Desire .. to want something ..

316
00:20:35,630 --> 00:20:38,064
You'll tame that desire and
live up to every moment of it.

317
00:20:38,975 --> 00:20:41,192
And then go on leaving yesterday behind.

318
00:20:41,990 --> 00:20:44,022
On and on .. higher and higher.

319
00:20:48,322 --> 00:20:50,879
Frustrated actress reads
lines for small audience.

320
00:20:51,947 --> 00:20:52,905
You could go on.

321
00:20:53,416 --> 00:20:55,134
Talent like yours doesn't die.

322
00:20:56,260 --> 00:20:58,390
You were a star once. You can be again.

323
00:20:58,912 --> 00:21:01,012
Uhuh .. an evil star, a jinx.

324
00:21:02,288 --> 00:21:03,675
You'd better run for your life.

325
00:21:04,968 --> 00:21:08,466
You can't possibly believe that
silly theatrical superstition.

326
00:21:09,075 --> 00:21:12,203
Well, two men who loved me are
dead and some financially ruined.

327
00:21:13,032 --> 00:21:14,060
Shows have folded.

328
00:21:14,318 --> 00:21:16,979
How can I possibly ignore it when
producers won't give me parts?

329
00:21:17,469 --> 00:21:19,106
Your breakfast is getting cold.

330
00:21:19,679 --> 00:21:22,774
And you'd better be getting back to
town if you want to change your duds.

331
00:21:23,091 --> 00:21:24,994
You know, there is
something in what you say.

332
00:21:25,363 --> 00:21:28,227
I don't want breakfast. I go with you.
- Why don't you stay out the week?

333
00:21:28,723 --> 00:21:31,514
No-one will be using the house, so I can
come down Saturday, and take you in.

334
00:21:31,717 --> 00:21:33,317
The rest and quiet will do you good.

335
00:21:33,533 --> 00:21:36,521
Helping me is like shaking hands with
the devil. The worst luck in the world.

336
00:21:37,032 --> 00:21:38,331
That's ridiculous.

337
00:21:39,354 --> 00:21:40,958
Do you really want to go back to town?

338
00:21:41,459 --> 00:21:42,595
I don't care.

339
00:21:43,781 --> 00:21:45,856
You wouldn't feel obligated
if you stayed, would you?

340
00:21:46,059 --> 00:21:47,998
Why should I?
What difference does it make?

341
00:21:48,279 --> 00:21:51,059
Of course. It doesn't make any
difference. Then you'll stay?

342
00:21:51,267 --> 00:21:53,246
Yes, yes! But stop asking me questions.

343
00:21:53,464 --> 00:21:56,911
Go on and boast to your friends about
fishing Joyce Heath out of the gutter.

344
00:21:57,893 --> 00:21:59,934
I won't mention it, I can assure you.

345
00:22:09,536 --> 00:22:12,912
Better watch her pretty closely. She's
on the verge of going off the deep end.

346
00:22:20,187 --> 00:22:22,505
Come and have your
breakfast before it gets cold.

347
00:22:22,745 --> 00:22:24,034
May I please have a drink?

348
00:22:24,883 --> 00:22:26,969
Fresh milk? Country sausage?

349
00:22:27,507 --> 00:22:29,469
Come and get it.
There's lots to tuck away.

350
00:22:29,676 --> 00:22:31,773
I asked for a drink. Where's the bottle?

351
00:22:32,418 --> 00:22:34,549
Yes dear .. after you've eaten.

352
00:22:34,825 --> 00:22:36,739
I don't want your greasy food.
I want a drink.

353
00:22:37,168 --> 00:22:38,029
Where is it?

354
00:22:38,232 --> 00:22:40,828
Now, it will only make you
more sick and fidgety.

355
00:22:41,070 --> 00:22:42,553
You're worn to a frazzle.

356
00:22:42,891 --> 00:22:44,926
What you need is rest and food.

357
00:22:45,254 --> 00:22:46,703
Where is it?
- Uh ..

358
00:22:47,449 --> 00:22:49,025
I don't know.
- You're a liar.

359
00:22:54,720 --> 00:22:57,298
Now, now, now, now.
- Give me the key.

360
00:22:58,229 --> 00:22:59,457
I haven't got it.

361
00:23:03,591 --> 00:23:04,929
My dear ..
- Leave me alone.

362
00:23:05,132 --> 00:23:05,861
My dear.

363
00:23:08,577 --> 00:23:09,734
You've cut yourself.

364
00:23:10,152 --> 00:23:13,528
I reckon it isn't the first time you've
been hurt getting things you shouldn't.

365
00:23:14,449 --> 00:23:16,648
Oh stop nagging me .. get out.

366
00:23:17,149 --> 00:23:18,413
Get <i>out</i> will you.

367
00:23:41,820 --> 00:23:42,406
Ah.

368
00:23:42,789 --> 00:23:44,789
'Phantom of delight' as Wordsworth says.

369
00:23:46,102 --> 00:23:47,833
That's a little thing
I thought up myself.

370
00:23:48,036 --> 00:23:49,222
And not bad either.

371
00:23:52,731 --> 00:23:55,522
And what's the little woman been doing?
- Shopping. You?

372
00:23:56,118 --> 00:23:57,696
Getting a check for a theater job.

373
00:23:58,672 --> 00:24:00,151
Next week I go in escrow.

374
00:24:00,634 --> 00:24:01,592
Grand, isn't it?

375
00:24:01,885 --> 00:24:04,120
And those estates will be your
masterpiece, Don. I know it.

376
00:24:04,600 --> 00:24:06,474
I've talked to more people
that are interested.

377
00:24:06,902 --> 00:24:07,915
They'd better be.

378
00:24:08,712 --> 00:24:10,829
When my creditors get through
subdividing my shirt ..

379
00:24:11,032 --> 00:24:13,440
There won't be enough of it left
to show on a blue serge suit.

380
00:24:14,490 --> 00:24:15,432
Stop worrying.

381
00:24:15,799 --> 00:24:18,360
By the way, I've come to take you to
the Polo matches. Teddy's playing.

382
00:24:18,988 --> 00:24:19,678
Teddy?

383
00:24:20,415 --> 00:24:22,716
You know, I often wonder why he
doesn't use a croquet mallet.

384
00:24:23,036 --> 00:24:24,685
He's on the ground most of the game.

385
00:24:25,420 --> 00:24:27,687
Will you hurry up?
We've missed the first chukka as it is.

386
00:24:27,924 --> 00:24:29,596
I'll take 4-1 on Teddy's collarbone.

387
00:24:29,866 --> 00:24:31,969
Nope. But I'll take 2-1 on a rib.

388
00:24:33,890 --> 00:24:35,199
Oh, I can't go.

389
00:24:35,870 --> 00:24:36,599
Why not?

390
00:24:36,802 --> 00:24:39,805
I've just remembered I've promised to
go down to the country this afternoon.

391
00:24:40,323 --> 00:24:41,007
Why?

392
00:24:41,681 --> 00:24:43,677
It's rather an interesting .. case.

393
00:24:45,127 --> 00:24:48,326
Remember the night you and I and
Teddy sneaked out of the Linden party?

394
00:24:48,763 --> 00:24:49,406
Well.

395
00:24:49,969 --> 00:24:52,086
Oh I forgot .. I promised not to tell.

396
00:24:52,935 --> 00:24:54,136
It sounds intriguing.

397
00:24:54,670 --> 00:24:56,369
Well it was a peculiar incident.

398
00:24:57,632 --> 00:24:59,637
I don't see any reason
why I shouldn't tell you.

399
00:25:00,613 --> 00:25:02,577
Nope, better not.
A promise is a promise.

400
00:25:03,005 --> 00:25:04,664
Will you be home by Sunday?
- Tonight.

401
00:25:05,123 --> 00:25:06,916
If you ask me to breakfast
Sunday morning ..

402
00:25:07,119 --> 00:25:10,424
I take you on the golf course, give you
a stroke a hole, and beat the pants ..

403
00:25:10,920 --> 00:25:12,091
We call them 'slacks'.

404
00:25:12,665 --> 00:25:13,623
You may kiss me.

405
00:25:16,082 --> 00:25:17,269
Goodbye. See you Sunday.

406
00:25:28,321 --> 00:25:29,657
Good evening, widow Williams.

407
00:25:31,255 --> 00:25:33,795
Staying to dinner Mister Don? Pot roast.

408
00:25:34,013 --> 00:25:37,194
Pot roast? With all those potatoes
and carrots and onions around it?

409
00:25:38,306 --> 00:25:40,568
It's a shame to disturb them.
They look so cozy.

410
00:25:41,762 --> 00:25:42,673
And turnips.

411
00:25:43,481 --> 00:25:44,259
Turnips?

412
00:25:45,251 --> 00:25:48,191
And what's the matter with turnips?
Turnips are good for you.

413
00:25:48,509 --> 00:25:50,064
They grow hair on your chest.

414
00:25:50,749 --> 00:25:51,707
Do you eat them?

415
00:25:52,048 --> 00:25:52,826
Sure.

416
00:25:53,624 --> 00:25:55,340
Mr Don, don't be pesky.

417
00:25:58,153 --> 00:25:59,270
How did you guess?

418
00:26:00,291 --> 00:26:01,680
She isn't exactly chatty.

419
00:26:02,098 --> 00:26:05,437
You'll get more folksy
conversation out of a snowman.

420
00:26:05,730 --> 00:26:08,448
Where is she now?
- Gone up the hill towards the barn.

421
00:26:08,870 --> 00:26:11,502
I'd better go and try and find her.
It looks like rain to me.

422
00:26:11,967 --> 00:26:15,016
Now that corn of mine has been
prophesying rain for 30 years.

423
00:26:16,172 --> 00:26:17,240
Excepting once.

424
00:26:18,212 --> 00:26:19,896
That was my own fault for trimming him.

425
00:26:20,821 --> 00:26:21,956
I'd better hurry then.

426
00:26:22,703 --> 00:26:24,650
When are you going to fetch
her home, Mister Don?

427
00:26:25,155 --> 00:26:26,608
Whenever she wants to go. Why?

428
00:26:27,959 --> 00:26:29,923
Nothing. I was just .. talking.

429
00:26:30,332 --> 00:26:31,891
I'll be glad when she's gone though.

430
00:26:32,726 --> 00:26:33,518
Why?

431
00:26:34,441 --> 00:26:36,814
You know, it's different
for a man like you.

432
00:26:37,572 --> 00:26:40,057
But a woman knows an awful
lot about another woman.

433
00:26:40,426 --> 00:26:41,633
And she's dangerous.

434
00:26:42,728 --> 00:26:45,144
A bad woman's got something
a good woman ain't.

435
00:26:45,607 --> 00:26:49,000
And a good woman is jealous of
that something, and afraid of it.

436
00:26:50,036 --> 00:26:51,461
I don't know what it is, but ..

437
00:26:52,272 --> 00:26:53,261
She's got it.

438
00:26:53,601 --> 00:26:57,018
Sounds to me as if you've been reading
bad translations of French novels.

439
00:26:58,000 --> 00:27:01,250
In the first place, I don't find Miss
Heath especially attractive off stage.

440
00:27:01,946 --> 00:27:04,348
And in the second place,
it's no concern of yours.

441
00:27:06,691 --> 00:27:09,990
I guess he's right. I'm an old fool
getting to be a regular busybody.

442
00:27:11,371 --> 00:27:12,442
Miss Heath.

443
00:27:16,366 --> 00:27:17,379
Miss Heath.

444
00:27:31,163 --> 00:27:32,014
Miss Heath.

445
00:27:36,771 --> 00:27:37,881
Hey .. wake up.

446
00:27:44,776 --> 00:27:45,765
Oh, it's you.

447
00:27:46,962 --> 00:27:47,948
On Saturday, I ..

448
00:27:48,671 --> 00:27:51,116
I fell asleep in a bar.
It all comes back to me now.

449
00:27:51,351 --> 00:27:54,857
Yes, it's also going to rain. It would
be good sense to come in out of it.

450
00:27:55,075 --> 00:27:56,431
That's merely hearsay.

451
00:27:59,327 --> 00:28:01,388
Would you hand me my
shoes and stockings please?

452
00:28:03,884 --> 00:28:04,815
Thanks.

453
00:28:05,336 --> 00:28:06,923
You know, you are looking much better.

454
00:28:08,191 --> 00:28:09,634
I've enjoyed this afternoon.

455
00:28:10,105 --> 00:28:12,356
Going barefoot and sleeping in the sun.

456
00:28:13,379 --> 00:28:16,236
Playing a sort of a Naiad in the jungle.

457
00:28:16,439 --> 00:28:18,046
What do you mean? What's a 'Naiad'?

458
00:28:18,312 --> 00:28:19,699
It's some sort of a wood nymph.

459
00:28:20,143 --> 00:28:22,823
I'm not .. I'm not very
much up on my sprites.

460
00:28:23,923 --> 00:28:26,748
I must say a 'Naiad' becomes
you better than a 'Maenad'.

461
00:28:28,279 --> 00:28:29,148
Fancy.

462
00:28:30,037 --> 00:28:31,053
What's a 'Maenad'?

463
00:28:31,806 --> 00:28:34,486
They were mythical women,
famous for their beauty and charm.

464
00:28:34,691 --> 00:28:36,419
Who attended the Dionysian rebels.

465
00:28:37,187 --> 00:28:39,560
They were always so carried
away by the wild madness that ..

466
00:28:39,763 --> 00:28:42,887
They ended up by dancing hysterically
over the edge of a cliff to destruction.

467
00:28:44,811 --> 00:28:47,478
Sorry, but I'm too tired
to be hysterical, and my ..

468
00:28:47,877 --> 00:28:49,779
My feet are much too sore
from going barefoot ..

469
00:28:49,985 --> 00:28:51,852
To stand the jar of
dancing over the cliff.

470
00:28:53,085 --> 00:28:54,475
By the way, I ..

471
00:28:55,498 --> 00:28:56,484
I got the sermon.

472
00:28:56,940 --> 00:28:57,626
Ha.

473
00:28:58,669 --> 00:29:02,515
There's one little piggy that's going to
market in a shocking state of nudity.

474
00:29:05,124 --> 00:29:07,440
I hope you don't mind me
borrowing some of your clothes.

475
00:29:07,768 --> 00:29:08,822
Not at all.

476
00:29:17,995 --> 00:29:18,917
Sorry.

477
00:29:25,118 --> 00:29:26,518
[ Thunderclap! ]

478
00:29:31,775 --> 00:29:33,591
Looks as if we're going
to have a cloudburst.

479
00:29:35,806 --> 00:29:37,221
What do you find so amusing?

480
00:29:38,272 --> 00:29:40,016
What do you find so disturbing?

481
00:29:42,228 --> 00:29:43,894
Come on, before we get drenched.

482
00:29:49,040 --> 00:29:51,189
Naiad or Maenad, nothing. Mermaids ..

483
00:29:51,547 --> 00:29:52,928
Ha .. come on.

484
00:30:04,091 --> 00:30:06,099
Land's sake, you're soaking wet.

485
00:30:06,531 --> 00:30:07,628
It's all your fault.

486
00:30:07,977 --> 00:30:10,186
If you'd used a corn-plaster,
this wouldn't have happened.

487
00:30:10,804 --> 00:30:14,075
You'd better be going back to town
Mr Don, before you have to go in an ark.

488
00:30:14,699 --> 00:30:16,283
You can't drive back in this rain.

489
00:30:16,967 --> 00:30:18,935
And why can't he, may I ask?

490
00:30:20,079 --> 00:30:22,490
Driving on that road will be
like touring in a full bathtub.

491
00:30:22,886 --> 00:30:24,316
I never thought of that.

492
00:30:24,774 --> 00:30:26,569
You'd better turn down
my bed, Mrs Williams.

493
00:30:26,861 --> 00:30:28,447
I'll get up early and drive in.

494
00:31:01,223 --> 00:31:02,612
Listen to that rain.

